@item @strong{-0}
@anchor{@strong{-0}}

Use NUL as delimiter.

Normally input lines will end in \n (newline). If they end in \0
(NUL), then use this option. It is useful for processing arguments
that may contain \n (newline).

Shorthand for @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}delimiter '\0'}.

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}delimiter}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}arg-file} @emph{input-file}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}arg-file} @emph{input-file}}

@item @strong{-a} @emph{input-file}
@anchor{@strong{-a} @emph{input-file}}

Use @emph{input-file} as input source.

If multiple @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}arg-file} are given, each @emph{input-file} will be treated as an
input source, and all combinations of input sources will be
generated. E.g. The file @strong{foo} contains @strong{1 2}, the file
@strong{bar} contains @strong{a b c}.  @strong{-a foo} @strong{-a bar} will result in the combinations
(1,a) (1,b) (1,c) (2,a) (2,b) (2,c). This is useful for replacing
nested for-loops.

If @emph{input-file} starts with @strong{+} the file will be linked to the
previous @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}arg-file} E.g. The file @strong{foo} contains @strong{1 2}, the file
@strong{bar} contains @strong{a b}.  @strong{-a foo} @strong{-a +bar} will result in the
combinations (1,a) (2,b) like @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}link} instead of generating all
combinations.

