See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}compress} @strong{$TMPDIR} @strong{$PARALLEL_REMOTE_TMPDIR}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tmux} (Long beta testing)
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tmux} (Long beta testing)}

Use @strong{tmux} for output. Start a @strong{tmux} session and run each job in a
window in that session. No other output will be produced.

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tmuxpane}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tmuxpane} (Long beta testing)
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tmuxpane} (Long beta testing)}

Use @strong{tmux} for output but put output into panes in the first window.
Useful if you want to monitor the progress of less than 100 concurrent
jobs.

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tmux}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}timeout} @emph{duration}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}timeout} @emph{duration}}

Time out for command. If the command runs for longer than @emph{duration}
seconds it will get killed as per @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}term-seq}.

If @emph{duration} is followed by a % then the timeout will dynamically be
computed as a percentage of the median average runtime of successful
jobs. Only values > 100% will make sense.

@emph{duration} is in seconds, but can be postfixed with s, m, h, or d.

See also: TIME POSTFIXES @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}term-seq} @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}retries}

