@anchor{@strong{-t}}

Print the job to be run on stderr (standard error).

See also: @strong{-v} @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}interactive}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transfer}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transfer}}

Transfer files to remote computers.

Shorthand for: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile @{@}}.

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile}.

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile} @emph{filename}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile} @emph{filename}}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tf} @emph{filename}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}tf} @emph{filename}}

Transfer @emph{filename} to remote computers.

@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile} is used with @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}sshlogin} to transfer files to the
remote computers. The files will be transferred using @strong{rsync} and
will be put relative to the work dir.

The @emph{filename} will normally contain a replacement string.

If the path contains /./ the remaining path will be relative to the
work dir (for details: see @strong{rsync}). If the work dir is
@strong{/home/user}, the transferring will be as follows:

@verbatim
  /tmp/foo/bar   => /tmp/foo/bar
  tmp/foo/bar    => /home/user/tmp/foo/bar
  /tmp/./foo/bar => /home/user/foo/bar
  tmp/./foo/bar  => /home/user/foo/bar
@end verbatim

@emph{Examples}

This will transfer the file @emph{foo/bar.txt} to the computer
@emph{server.example.com} to the file @emph{$HOME/foo/bar.txt} before running
@strong{wc foo/bar.txt} on @emph{server.example.com}:

@verbatim
  echo foo/bar.txt | parallel --transferfile {} \
    --sshlogin server.example.com wc
@end verbatim

This will transfer the file @emph{/tmp/foo/bar.txt} to the computer
@emph{server.example.com} to the file @emph{/tmp/foo/bar.txt} before running
@strong{wc /tmp/foo/bar.txt} on @emph{server.example.com}:

@verbatim
  echo /tmp/foo/bar.txt | parallel --transferfile {} \
    --sshlogin server.example.com wc
@end verbatim

This will transfer the file @emph{/tmp/foo/bar.txt} to the computer
@emph{server.example.com} to the file @emph{foo/bar.txt} before running
@strong{wc ./foo/bar.txt} on @emph{server.example.com}:

@verbatim
  echo /tmp/./foo/bar.txt | parallel --transferfile {} \
    --sshlogin server.example.com wc {= s:.*/\./:./: =}
@end verbatim

@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile} is often used with @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}return} and @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}cleanup}. A
shorthand for @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile @{@}} is @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transfer}.

@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}transferfile} is ignored when used with @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}sshlogin :} or when
not used with @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}sshlogin}.

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}workdir} @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}sshlogin} @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}basefile} @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}return}
@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}cleanup}

