@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-sockets-instead-of-threads}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-sockets-instead-of-threads}}

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cores-instead-of-threads}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cores-instead-of-threads}
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cores-instead-of-threads}}

@item @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cpus-instead-of-cores} (obsolete)
@anchor{@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cpus-instead-of-cores} (obsolete)}

Determine how GNU @strong{parallel} counts the number of CPUs.

GNU @strong{parallel} uses this number when the number of jobslots
(@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}jobs}) is computed relative to the number of CPUs (e.g. 100% or
+1).

CPUs can be counted in three different ways:

@table @asis
@item sockets
@anchor{sockets}

The number of filled CPU sockets (i.e. the number of physical chips).

@item cores
@anchor{cores}

The number of physical cores (i.e. the number of physical compute
cores).

@item threads
@anchor{threads}

The number of hyperthreaded cores (i.e. the number of virtual
cores - with some of them possibly being hyperthreaded)

@end table

Normally the number of CPUs is computed as the number of CPU
threads. With @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-sockets-instead-of-threads} or
@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cores-instead-of-threads} you can force it to be computed as
the number of filled sockets or number of cores instead.

Most users will not need these options.

@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-cpus-instead-of-cores} is a (misleading) alias for
@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}use-sockets-instead-of-threads} and is kept for backwards
compatibility.

See also: @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}number-of-threads} @strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}number-of-cores}
@strong{@asis{}-@asis{}-@asis{}number-of-sockets}

